d Scottish: habitational name from any of the many places called Mor(e)ton, named with Old English <i>mōr</i> ‘moor’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. There has probably been some confusion with   Morten  , and perhaps also with   Murton  . This English name has also been established in Ireland since the 13th century.","American shortened and altered form of Swedish <b>Mårtensson</b> or <b>Mortensson</b> (see   Martenson   and   Mortenson  ), which could also be substituted for the Finnish cognate <b>Marttinen</b>.","French: shortened form of   Moreton   3."]}]},{"name":"Eustace","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Old French form of the Late Greek names <i>Eustakhios</i> and <i>Eustathios</i>. These were evidently of separate origin, the former derived from <i>eu</i> ‘well, good’ + <i>stakhys</i> ‘grapes’, the latter from <i>eu</i> + <i>stēnai</i> ‘to stand’. However, the tradition is very confused. The name was introduced in this form to Britain by the Normans, among whom it was popular as a result of the fame of  St Eustace , a Norman nobleman who was said to have been converted to Christianity by the vision of a crucifix between the antlers of the stag he was hunting."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":20,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":29,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Eustace de Morteyn was born in 1195, in Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England, his father, Eustace de Morteyn, was 27 and his mother, Hillaria Salvein, was 31. He married Eincina Ruffus in 1213, in Nottinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died in 1234, in Tilsworth, Bedfordshire, England, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1195–1234":"1195–1234","–1247":"–1247","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","1217–1283":"1217–1283","1221–1281":"1221–1281","1227–1299":"1227–1299","1233–1284":"1233–1284","1168–1223":"1168–1223","1165–1216":"1165–1216","20 February 1223":"20. veebruar 1223","1165":"1165","1284":"1284","1195":"1195","1283":"1283","1281":"1281","1217":"1217","1216":"1216","1227":"1227","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1247":"1247","1213":"1213","1224":"1224","1234":"1234","1223":"1223","1168":"1168","1233":"1233","1299":"1299","1221":"1221","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Tilsworth, Bedfordshire, England":"Tilsworth, Bedfordshire, England","England":"England","Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England","Tillsworth,Bedford,England,Great Britain":"Tilsworth, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wollaton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Wollaton, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1195–1234":"1195–1234","–1247":"–1247","1205–Female":"1205–Kuollut","1217–1283":"1217–1283","1221–1281":"1221–1281","1227–1299":"1227–1299","1233–1284":"1233–1284","1168–1223":"1168–1223","1165–1216":"1165–1216","20 February 1223":"20. helmikuuta 1223","1165":"1165","1284":"1284","1195":"1195","1283":"1283","1281":"1281","1217":"1217","1216":"1216","1227":"1227","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1247":"1247","1213":"1213","1224":"1224","1234":"1234","1223":"1223","1168":"1168","1233":"1233","1299":"1299","1221":"1221","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","T